(a) NB w/o smoothing

macron_prior <- 4/7
lepen_prior <- 3/7

# Macron probability:
(macron_pr <- macron_prior * (1/20) * (1/20) * (1/20) * (2/20) * (1/20))
## [1] 3.571429e-07
# log prob
log(macron_pr)
## [1] -14.84513
# LePen probability:
(lepen_pr <- lepen_prior * (2/15) * (2/15) * (2/15) * (1/15) * 0)
## [1] 0
# log prob
log(lepen_pr)
## [1] -Inf

(b) With Laplace smoothing

# Vocabulary size:

Question 2

2(a): Load data and code positive/negative label based on median score

samp <- read.csv("yelp_reviews.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

med<-median(samp$stars)

samp$positive <- as.numeric(samp$stars > med)


# Percent positive
sum(samp$positive) / length(samp$positive)
## [1] 0.3554
# Percent negative:

1 - sum(samp$positive) / length(samp$positive)
## [1] 0.6446

Question 3: Dictionaries

3(a): Hu & Liu sentiment

  • Your results may vary depending on pre-processing etc.
# Read in positive and negative words

pos<-read.table("positive-words.txt", stringsAsFactors = F)
neg<-read.table("negative-words.txt", stringsAsFactors = F)

pos<-as.character(pos$V1)
neg<-as.character(neg$V1)

sentiment_dict <- dictionary(list(pos=pos, neg=neg))

# Pre-process
yelp_dfm <- dfm(samp$text, remove_punct = TRUE, stem = FALSE, dictionary = sentiment_dict)

# Calculate sentiment score
samp$Sent <- as.numeric(yelp_dfm[,'pos']) - as.numeric(yelp_dfm[, 'neg'])

# Calculate binary vector (1 = positive, 0 = negative)
samp$sent_pos <- as.numeric(samp$Sent >= 0)

# Percent positive

sum(samp$sent_pos) / length(samp$sent_pos)
## [1] 0.8986
# Percent negative

1 - sum(samp$sent_pos) / length(samp$sent_pos)
## [1] 0.1014

3(b): Histogram

hist(samp$Sent)

percent_positive <- mean(samp$sent_pos)*100

# Find number of positive sentiment reviews
pos_sent <- length(which(samp$sent_pos==TRUE))

Question 4: Naive Bayes

4(a)

# Start from the original data again
NB_reviews <- samp

true_label <- factor(NB_reviews$positive)

label_NB <- true_label
label_NB[1:(0.8*length(label_NB))] <- NA # 80% in the test set is labeled NA

NB_dfm <- dfm(NB_reviews$text, stem = TRUE,  remove_punct = TRUE, remove = stopwords("english"))

NBmodel <- textmodel_nb(NB_dfm, label_NB, smooth = 1, prior = "uniform") 

NBpredict <- predict(NBmodel, newdata = NB_dfm[is.na(label_NB), ])

# Confusion matrix (of test set)

confusion_mat_nb <- table(true_label[is.na(label_NB)], as.numeric(NBpredict$nb.predicted))

Question 6: SVM

  • Your results may vary depending on pre-processing etc.

6(b)

# Let's train the linear SVM model
SVM_reviews <- samp[1:1000, ]

dtm <- create_matrix(SVM_reviews$text, language="english", stemWords = FALSE, removePunctuation = FALSE, removeStopwords = TRUE)

break_accuracy_lin<-vector()

for(i in 1:9) {
  training_break <- as.integer(0.1*i*nrow(SVM_reviews))
  
  container      <- create_container(dtm, true_label, 
                                     trainSize = 1:training_break,
                                     testSize = (training_break+1):nrow(SVM_reviews), 
                                     virgin = FALSE
                                     )
  
  cv.svm <- cross_validate(container, nfold= 10, algorithm = 'SVM', kernel = 'linear')
  break_accuracy_lin[i]<-cv.svm$meanAccuracy
}

6(c)

# Let's train the model -- with radial kernel
break_accuracy_rad <- vector()

for(i in 1:9) {
  training_break <- as.integer(0.1*i*nrow(SVM_reviews))
  container      <- create_container(dtm, 
                                     true_label, 
                                     trainSize=1:training_break,
                                     testSize=(training_break+1):nrow(SVM_reviews), 
                                     virgin=FALSE
                                     )
  
  cv.svm <- cross_validate(container, nfold = 10, algorithm = 'SVM', kernel = 'radial')
  break_accuracy_rad[i] <- cv.svm$meanAccuracy
}
